Loading packages and helper functions

rm(list=ls())

library(tidyr)
library(stringr)

library(ggplot2)

sem <- function(x) {sd(x, na.rm=TRUE) / sqrt(length(x))}
ci95 <- function(x) {sem(x) * 1.96}
theme_set(theme_bw())

## NA functions
na.mean <- function(x) {mean(x,na.rm=T)}
na.median <- function(x) {median(x,na.rm=T)}
na.sum <- function(x) {sum(x,na.rm=T)}
na.sd <- function(x) {sd(x,na.rm=T)}

## convert to number
to.n <- function(x) {
  as.numeric(as.character(x))
}

## get stars for significance testing
getstars <- function(x) {
  if (x > .1) {return("")}
  if (x < .001) {return("***")}
  if (x < .01) {return("**")}
  if (x < .05) {return("*")}
}

d$savings = as.numeric(d$savings)

Converting delaytime to years and savings to total savings. Creating a log(savings) variable to compare to original study.

d$delaydiv <- ifelse(d$timeMetric == "fine", 365, 1) #Creating a denominator, depending on condition
d$delaytimetot = d$delaytime / d$delaydiv #Calculating time to wait in years
range(d$delaytimetot, na.rm = T) #Checking range of new variable
## [1] 0 1
d$savingdiv <- ifelse((d$timeMetric == "fine") & (d$incrAction) == "incremental", 10950, 
                       ifelse((d$timeMetric == "gross") & (d$incrAction == "incremental"), 30, 1)) #Creating multiplier, depending on condition (only necessary for incremental action conditions)
d$savingtot = d$savings * d$savingdiv #Calculating overall retirement savings
range(d$savingtot, na.rm = T) #Checking range
## [1]      100 10950000
#str(d)
d$logsavingtot = log(d$savingtot) #Creating log(savings) using natural log
range(d$logsavingtot) #checking range
## [1]  4.60517 16.20885

Exclusion Criteria

  • Did not respond to a DV or gave uninterpretable response
  • Gave responses mean+3SD for WHEN to save (as per original paper)
  • Gave responses mean+3SD for HOW MUCH to save
  • Would wait > 10950 in fine-grained condition
  • Would wait > 30 years in gross-grained condition

Exclude people here.

Sanity check

Now that we have excluded any invalid responses, the range of values for raw delaytime variable should be 1, 10,950 for fine-grained and 1, 30 for gross-grained. You cant have said that youll wait longer to begin to save than is indicated in prompt.

range(d$delaytime[d$timeMetric == "fine"], na.rm = T) #can't wait more than 10950 days
## [1]   0 365
range(d$delaytime[d$timeMetric == "gross"], na.rm = T) #can't wait more than 30yrs
## [1] 0.0 0.5

Also expect that the mean(raw delaytime) for fine-grained condition should be larger than (or equal to) mean(raw delaytime) for gross-grained condition

delayt = t.test(delaytime ~ timeMetric, d) #expect a significant difference

t = 1.12, p = 0.38

Randomization check

There should be NO effect of incremental action condition on time/delay to save because that variable was not into play until after the delay question was answered

delaytimemean2 = d %>% 
  group_by(incrAction) %>%
  summarise(mean=mean(delaytimetot, na.rm = T), sd=sd(delaytimetot, na.rm = T), n = sum(!is.na(delaytimetot)), sem = sem(delaytimetot))
#delaytimemean2

ggplot(delaytimemean2, aes(x=incrAction, y = mean)) + 
  geom_bar(position=position_dodge(), stat="identity",
           colour="black", # Use black outlines,
           size=.3) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-sem, ymax=mean+sem),
                size=.4,
                width=.2,                    # Width of the error bars
                position=position_dodge(.9)) +
  xlab("Incremental Action Condition") +
  ylab("Years to Delay") +
  ggtitle("Randomization check - Years to delay retirement saving") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 16)

Planned Analyses

Covariates

In the original paper, age, income, and education were not significantly correlated with WHEN to save, but income was positively correlated with AMOUNT to save. For both DVs, the authors ran regressions controlling for these 3 covariates, and not controlling for them, and interpretation of results was unchanged with demographic controls.

Relationship between demographics and WHEN to save:

Main analyses

There were two main analyses in the original paper. The first was whether there were differences between time metric condition on WHEN to begin saving for retirement. The second was whether there were differences between time metric conditions or incremental action conditions on how much to save. In both cases, the authors ran a regression with no demographic controls, and a model with demographic controls (age, education, income). Only income significantly predicted amount to save, but controlling for demographics did not change the interpretation of either outcome.

Comparing means from my sample to means in original paper

Determining how similar my means are to those in the original paper.

Means of when to start saving

Mean years to delay in fine-grained condition = 0.45 years

t.test(d$delaytimetot[d$timeMetric == "fine"], mu = .45) #comparing to mean(fine) in original study
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  d$delaytimetot[d$timeMetric == "fine"]

Exploratory analyses

Investigating the correlation between delaying to save and total savings

If I think I need to save a lot, perhaps I feel that I should get started sooner, rather than wait (negative correlation).

#cor.test(d$savingtot.s, d$delaytimetot.s)
d0 = na.omit(d)

Next steps

Should we replicate the original results, or even partially replicate, I would love to explore mediators. A later study in the original paper concluded that fine-grained time metrics dont make the future feel nearer. Instead, it makes people feel more connected to their future self. However, the future self measure was confounded with time metric, so Id like to find an independent way to measure it.
